{"id":"1403.3180","submitter":"Holger F. Hofmann","authors":"Changliang Ren and Holger F. Hofmann","title":"Simultaneous suppression of time and energy uncertainties in a\n  single-photon frequency comb state","comments":"9 pages, including 2 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 89, 053823 (2014)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.89.053823","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A single photon prepared in a time-energy state described by a frequency comb\ncombines the extreme precision of energy defined by a single tooth of the comb\nwith a high sensitivity to small shifts in time defined by the narrowness of a\nsingle pulse in the long sequence of pulses that describe the frequency comb\nstate in the time domain. We show how this simultaneous suppression of time and\nenergy uncertainties can be described by a separation of scales and compare\nthis with the suppression of uncertainties in the two particle correlations of\nan entangled state. To illustrate the sensitivity of the frequency comb states\nto small shifts in time and frequency, we consider the Hong-Ou-Mandel dips\nobserved in two-photon interference when both time- and frequency shifts\nbetween the input photons are varied. It is shown that the interference of two\nphotons in equivalent frequency comb states results in a two dimensional\nHong-Ou-Mandel dip that is narrow in both time and frequency, while the\ncorresponding entangled photon pairs are only sensitive to temporal shifts.\nFrequency comb states thus represent a unique and different approach towards\nquantum operations beyond the uncertainty limit.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Mar 2014 07:35:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-05-19"}
